@Node "CFG_LOAD" "MachV.guide/CFG_LOAD"
@Next "CFG_SAVE"
@Prev "CFG_SELECT"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

CFG_LOAD
========

   This function loads a new configuration (prefs) file. It takes one
argument.

CFG_LOAD"ENVARC:MachV/backup.prefs"
     Load the prefs file ENVARC:MachV/backup.prefs.


@EndNode

@Node "CFG_SAVE" "MachV.guide/CFG_SAVE"
@Next "EXE_AUTO"
@Prev "CFG_LOAD"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

CFG_SAVE
========

   This function saves a configuration (prefs) file. It takes one
optional argument, a file name. If no file name, the current name is
used.

CFG_SAVE"ENVARC:MachV/MachV.prefs"
     Save the prefs file ENVARC:MachV/MachV.prefs.


@EndNode

@Node "EXE_AUTO" "MachV.guide/EXE_AUTO"
@Next "EXE_CMD"
@Prev "CFG_SAVE"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

EXE_AUTO
========

   This function executes a macro at a specific time. It takes one to
seven arguments. The first is the time, optionally then, either the
date, or day(s) of the week. The standard AmigaDos wild cards ? and #
may be used in these arguments.

EXE_AUTO"17:35" ...more macro functions...
     Execute this macro at 5:35pm.

EXE_AUTO"15:30,12-09-93" ...more macro functions...
     Execute this macro at 3:30pm on 12-09-93.

EXE_AUTO"15:30,??-05-??" ...more macro functions...
     Execute this macro at 3:30pm on the 5th of every month.

EXE_AUTO"5:00,Mon" ...more macro functions...
     Execute this macro at 5:00am on every Monday.

EXE_AUTO"15:30,Mon,Wed,Fri" ...more macro functions...
     Execute this macro at 3:30pm on every Monday, Wednesday and Friday.

EXE_AUTO"+30" ...more macro functions...
     Execute every 30 minutes.

EXE_AUTO"" ...more macro functions...
     Execute when MachV is first run.

   See @{"Auto Executing Macro" Link "Auto Executing Macro"}.


@EndNode

@Node "EXE_CMD" "MachV.guide/EXE_CMD"
@Next "EXE_AREXX_COMMAND"
@Prev "EXE_AUTO"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

EXE_CMD
=======

   This function runs a program. It takes one or two arguments.

EXE_CMD"Run ProWrite"
     Run the program "ProWrite"

EXE_CMD"Packer20,PowerPack"
     If the window or screen title is found, bring it to the front,
     otherwise run the program Packer20.

EXE_CMD"Run FinalCopy,Final Copy"
     Run FinalCopy unless the screen titled "Final Copy" is open.

EXE_CMD"${shell}"
     Environment variables may also be used.

   See @{"Executing Programs" Link "Executing Programs"}, and See @{"Environment Variables" Link "Environment Variables"}.


@EndNode

@Node "EXE_AREXX_COMMAND" "MachV.guide/EXE_AREXX_COMMAND"
@Next "EXE_AREXX_STRING"
@Prev "EXE_CMD"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

EXE_AREXX_COMMAND
=================

   This function eliminates the need for "rx" or "run rx" and also
allows scripts with just MachV macros without "address MACHV_REXX". It
takes one or two arguments.

EXE_AREXX_COMMAND"test.rexx"
     Execute the program test.rexx.

EXE_AREXX_COMMAND"test,results"
     Execute the program test.mach (default extension .mach) and store
     any returned value in the environment variable "results".

   See @{"ARexx" Link "ARexx"}, and See @{"Environment Variables" Link "Environment Variables"}.


@EndNode

@Node "EXE_AREXX_STRING" "MachV.guide/EXE_AREXX_STRING"
@Next "EXE_SETMACH"
@Prev "EXE_AREXX_COMMAND"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

EXE_AREXX_STRING
================

   This function will instruct ARexx to execute the first argument as an
ARexx program. It takes one or two arguments.

AREXX_STRING"return time(hours),results"
     Execute the ARexx function time(hours) and store the results in
     "results".

EXE_AREXX_COMMAND"test,results"
     Execute the program test.mach (default extension .mach) and store
     any returned value in the environment variable "results".

   See @{"ARexx" Link "ARexx"}, and See @{"Environment Variables" Link "Environment Variables"}.


@EndNode

@Node "EXE_SETMACH" "MachV.guide/EXE_SETMACH"
@Next "MAC_SELECT_NAMED"
@Prev "EXE_AREXX_STRING"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

EXE_SETMACH
===========

   This function runs SetMachV. It takes no arguments. If SetMachV is
already running, it will be brought to the front.

   EXE_SETMACH

   See @{"SetMachV" Link "SetMachV"}.


@EndNode

@Node "MAC_SELECT_NAMED" "MachV.guide/MAC_SELECT_NAMED"
@Next "MAC_EXECUTE_NAMED"
@Prev "EXE_SETMACH"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

MAC_SELECT_NAMED
================

   This function opens a list box to select a macro name from and
executes that macro. It takes one optional argument.

MAC_SELECT_NAMED"Macro Selection"
     Open the list box. "Macro Selection" is the optional title, it
     replaces the default "Select A Name" title.


@EndNode

@Node "MAC_EXECUTE_NAMED" "MachV.guide/MAC_EXECUTE_NAMED"
@Next "MAC_FINISH"
@Prev "MAC_SELECT_NAMED"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

MAC_EXECUTE_NAMED
=================

   This function executes a named macro. It takes one argument, the
macro name.

MAC_EXECUTE_NAMED"zoom"
     Execute a macro named "zoom".


@EndNode

@Node "MAC_FINISH" "MachV.guide/MAC_FINISH"
@Next "MAC_MACROS"
@Prev "MAC_EXECUTE_NAMED"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

MAC_FINISH
==========

   This function completes a word or phrase by executing a macro based
on characters already typed that match a macro's name. It takes no
arguments.

   MAC_FINISH

   If you have a macro "Polyglot Software" (with quotes) with a name of
"Polyglot" (without quotes) attached to the key <F1>, and you type
Pol<F1>, then "yglot Software" will be typed out. In other words, it
skips what you have already typed and then sends the rest of the macro
as keystrokes. You may include special keys like "\N". The macro must be
enclosed in quotes. The matching is case insensitive. It will attempt
local then global macros.


@EndNode

@Node "MAC_MACROS" "MachV.guide/MAC_MACROS"
@Next "MAC_RECORD_KEYED"
@Prev "MAC_FINISH"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

MAC_MACROS
==========

   This function turns all macros on and off. It takes one argument.

MAC_MACROS"Tog"
     Toggle macros on or off.

MAC_MACROS"Off"
     Turn macros off.

MAC_MACROS"On"
     Turn macros on.

   You must use the same hotkey to enable macros. You cannot depend on
"Hold Qualifier" to add the appropriate qualifiers when enabling macros.


@EndNode

@Node "MAC_RECORD_KEYED" "MachV.guide/MAC_RECORD_KEYED"
@Next "MAC_RECORD_NAMED"
@Prev "MAC_MACROS"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

MAC_RECORD_KEYED
================

   This function starts or stops macro recording. It takes no arguments.

   MAC_RECORD_KEYED

   See @{"Recording Macros" Link "Recording Macros"}.


@EndNode

@Node "MAC_RECORD_NAMED" "MachV.guide/MAC_RECORD_NAMED"
@Next "MAC_QUICK_EDIT"
@Prev "MAC_RECORD_KEYED"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

MAC_RECORD_NAMED
================

   This function starts or stops macro recording to a named macro. It
takes no arguments.

   MAC_RECORD_NAMED

   See @{"Recording Macros" Link "Recording Macros"}.


@EndNode

@Node "MAC_QUICK_EDIT" "MachV.guide/MAC_QUICK_EDIT"
@Next "MAC_DELETE"
@Prev "MAC_RECORD_NAMED"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

MAC_QUICK_EDIT
==============

   This function opens a window to edit a macro. It takes no arguments.

   MAC_QUICK_EDIT

   See @{"Quick Edit" Link "Quick Edit"}.


@EndNode

@Node "MAC_DELETE" "MachV.guide/MAC_DELETE"
@Next "MOU_LBD"
@Prev "MAC_QUICK_EDIT"
@Toc "Macro Functions"

MAC_DELETE
==========

   This function deletes a macro. It takes one optional argument, a
macro name. If no name is provided, this function will delete the macro
that contains it.  Deletion occurs after the entire macro has executed.

MAC_DELETE
     Delete this macro.

MAC_DELETE"Temp"
     Delete a macro named "Temp"


@EndNode

